{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502539"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1870"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.77,0.05,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1870"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78024"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5646"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44841"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents by himself to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of his hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His conditions are well-controlled on amlodipine and metformin. He lives independently and manages his own affairs. During the consultation some routine blood tests are arranged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELater that day, his daughter calls the clinic requesting information about her father\u0027s test results and medications, expressing concern about his wellbeing. She states she is his primary carer and has power of attorney. She provides documentation confirming her legal status.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response to the daughter\u0027s request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide only basic information about his medications","Discuss results after confirming her identity","Obtain patient consent before sharing any information","Share information as she has power of attorney","Arrange a joint consultation with both present"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the fundamental principle of patient confidentiality in medical practice. \u003Cstrong\u003EObtaining patient consent\u003C/strong\u003E before sharing any medical information is essential, even with close family members. Although the daughter has power of attorney and is the primary carer, this only becomes relevant for medical decision-making when a patient lacks capacity. As this patient is competent and manages his own affairs, he retains the right to control access to his medical information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing information due to power of attorney\u003C/strong\u003E status would be inappropriate while the patient has capacity. Power of attorney only becomes active for medical decisions when a patient loses capacity to make their own decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding basic medication information\u003C/strong\u003E would still constitute a breach of confidentiality. Even seemingly minor details about a patient\u0027s care require consent before disclosure, regardless of the requester\u0027s relationship to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussing results after confirming identity\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as identity verification does not override the need for patient consent, even for someone with documented power of attorney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging a joint consultation\u003C/strong\u003E without first obtaining the patient\u0027s consent would not respect his autonomy and right to privacy. While joint consultations can be valuable, they should only occur with the patient\u0027s agreement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers must maintain professional boundaries and respect patient confidentiality, even when family members have good intentions and legal authority. The appropriate approach is to explain to the daughter that patient confidentiality prevents sharing any information without explicit consent from her father while he retains capacity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patient confidentiality must be maintained even with close family members unless explicit consent is obtained from a competent patient.","Healthcare providers should not disclose or discuss patient information with family members without the patient\u0027s permission, even if they have power of attorney.","When patients have capacity, they control who has access to their medical information, regardless of their family or carer relationships."],"references":["Bourke J, Wessely S. Confidentiality. BMJ 2008; 336:888-91."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T08:33:58+10:30","updatedAt":"202